<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Observer: Heavy at Trevi
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sifis Valyrakis, Greece's new undersecretary for public order, is causing
quite a stir in Brussels.
He is terribly popular on his native island of Crete, where he has been
elected to parliament at every election since 1977. But he does have a
rather unusual pedigree.
He was arrested twice in the mid-1970s, first for smuggling a boat load of
weapons through the Aegean, then for organising armed groups in Greece who
were reportedly trained by Palestinian guerrillas.
Unkind mutterings within the government suggest he was given a junior
minister's job in order to make up the numbers of Cretan deputies - the
island being more solidly socialist than anywhere else in the land.
Which does nothing to quiet some in Brussels who wonder whether Valyrakis
should be allowed to participate in meetings of the Trevi group. Composed of
EU interior and public order ministers, it deals with immigration, border
security and counter-terrorism matters. At least Valyrakis would know what
he was talking about.
</TEXT>
