<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
John Major's recent cabinet re-shuffle was a pathetic non event when
compared with Harold Macmillan's Night of the Long Knives in August 1962
when he summarily sacked a third of his cabinet. Timewatch (BBC 2 at 8pm)
examines this cathartic event, mixing rare archive footage and interviews
with some of the ministers involved. Michael Cockerell's documentary airs
the idea that Macmillan was launching a pre-emptive strike to thwart a plot
to overthrow him.
Just how big a disaster The Living Soap (BBC 2 at midnight) has turned out
to be is indicated by this late slot for the final two episodes. The idea of
filming a group of Manchester students as they shared a house, and their
lives, came up against some unmanageable egos. The problem was that none of
the participants could be other than extroverts who saw taking part in the
project as the first step towards a career in the media.
Richard Littlejohn - Live and Uncut (ITV at 10.30) is determined to make
this as controversial as his tabloid newspaper column and his radio
programme.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
