<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Scottish water schemes attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was accused yesterday of privatising Scotland's water
industry through the back door by urging local authorities to engage
private-sector companies to build, operate and own water and sewerage
installations.
Mr Archy Kirkwood, a Liberal Democrat MP, said the use of build, own and
operate schemes, known as BOO, was 'virtual privatisation'. It would negate
the government's promise that Scotland's water and sewerage industry would
not be privatised, unlike the industry in England and Wales.
It is believed the first BOO scheme for a Scottish water or sewerage project
could go to tender in the autumn, following the drafting of specimen tenders
by a team involving the Scottish Office, the private sector and a regional
council.
The use of BOO schemes is favoured by the Scottish Office as a way of
financing the upgrading of Scotland's water and sewerage industry in the
next 15 years to bring it into line with European Union standards.
Under a BOO scheme a private consortium of banks and construction companies
contracts with a local authority to build a sewerage plant. It would then
own it and operate it under contract with the regional council or, after
1996, the three new publicly owned water authorities.
From the government's point of view the advantage of BOO schemes is that
they allow the public sector to undertake large capital spending projects
without increasing the public sector borrowing requirement, because councils
do not have to borrow to finance them.
A list of 14 Scottish water and sewerage projects worth about Pounds 1bn
suitable for BOO financing was published by the Treasury last November.
A project team - including the construction company Balfour Beatty, the
French-owned water company Degremont, two banks and Lothian regional council
 -has been studying the technicalities of BOO schemes in Scotland.
Although the Scottish Office said yesterday that it was up to regional
councils whether they went ahead with BOO schemes it is understood that it
is unwilling to give councils permission to borrow to finance them.
They could, however, finance smaller schemes out of their current budget.
Lothian region has allowed its officials to consider the BOO system but
other councils, such as Strathclyde, have refused to get involved.
</TEXT>
