<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Slaughters heads takeover league
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Slaughter and May has been the leading law firm advising in public takeovers
in the first half of this year, it emerged yesterday.
The firm advised companies or financial advisers in five deals worth Pounds
1.63bn, according to Acquisitions Monthly magazine, which ranks law firms by
the value of the takeovers in which they have acted as advisers.
Among the deals which enabled Slaughters to top the league table was the
Granada Group's Pounds 766m takeover of London Weekend Television, when the
law firm acted for LWT. Slaughter's also represented Westland in its
acquisition by GKN.
Ashurst Morris Crisp took second place in the table, having worked on three
deals worth Pounds 1.1bn. These included acting for MAI in its takeover of
Anglia Television. The firm has worked closely with the banking world and
two deals worth Pounds 780m pushed it to the top of the table of legal
advisers acting for financial advisers.
The statistics again show the continued domination of the leading national
law firms. The strength of regional firms is demonstrated by
Birmingham-based Wragge &amp; Co appearing in the table for the first time,
ranked tenth. The firm participated in two deals worth Pounds 92m.
Slaughters was also the leading adviser on private takeovers in the January
to June period. It acted in 24 deals worth Pounds 2.87bn. Among these were
the Pounds 1.5bn sale of the Rover Group to BMW.
Linklaters &amp; Paines was second in the private takeovers table, advising in
16 bids which were worth Pounds 2.1bn. Norton Rose was third with six deals
totalling Pounds 1.6bn.
According to the magazine most lawyers in the mergers and acquisitions
market are quietly confident that the level of business will be sustained
for the rest of the year.
