<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Tesco is called on to increase local sourcing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tesco was urged yesterday to make its takeover of William Low, the
Dundee-based supermarket chain, more acceptable to Scottish public opinion
by obtaining more of its goods from Scotland.
The battle for Wm Low - won by Tesco over J. Sainsbury - has caused dismay
in Scotland because of the disappearance of another of Scotland's small
number of quoted companies and because of the intended closure of Wm Low's
headquarters in Dundee, which employs 300 people.
Few Wm Low stores in Scotland or northern England are likely to close
because of Tesco's small presence north of the border, while Scottish food
and drink suppliers could gain a larger market.
Dr Jeremy Bray, Labour MP for Motherwell South, yesterday wrote to Sir Ian
MacLaurin, chairman of Tesco, saying that it would be 'a material factor'
with Scots if he were able to say Tesco would increase the sourcing of its
products in Scotland for sale throughout Britain.
In its original offer in July Tesco said it 'intended to continue Wm Low's
policy of encouraging Scottish suppliers and to offer them the potential to
benefit from the wider market served by Tesco'.
Tesco has since said it plans to set up an office in Scotland to handle the
buying of goods and the marketing of the company in Scotland. Yesterday it
said its existing 16 Scottish stores would be given 'a Scottish flavour'.
