<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Lloyd's outlines outsider reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London yesterday unveiled proposals to expand the membership of
outsiders on its ruling council and to change the voting structure of the
insurance market.
It will ensure that there are six working, six external and six nominated
members of the insurance market on the council from the start of next year.
It will also change from the current position of 'one member, one vote' to a
weighted system. Allocation of votes will be based on the overall
underwriting capacity of each Name, the individuals whose assets have
traditionally supported the market.
The changes are among the 18 recommendations approved in full by the council
on Wednesday which were made in a report, co-ordinated by Mr Mark Sheldon, a
former president of the Law Society, and completed in June.
The Association of Lloyd's Names, the biggest Names group, gave a 'qualified
welcome' to the proposals, saying that the change to voting rights would
help give a say to Names regardless of their outstanding liabilities.
Separately, the Lloyd's council said yesterday that it was investigating
ways to close off underwriting syndicates that remain 'open' in years since
1985 as a result of outstanding liabilities. Open years cause considerable
uncertainty to Names and make it impossible for them to cease being members
of the market.
The new initiative - if implemented - would extend the principle to more
recent years, covering such liabilities as catastrophe reinsurance.
Lloyd's also said yesterday that the council had invited Mr David Rowland,
the chairman, to extend his term for a year beyond the three years expiring
at the end of next year.
</TEXT>
