<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / France unhappy with allies on Algeria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France yesterday accused Britain, Germany and the US of failing to crack
down on fundamentalist opponents of the Algiers government on their soil.
The Dutch, meanwhile, closed their Algiers embassy and Belgium urged its
nationals to leave the country after the killing of five French police and
consular officials on Wednesday.
As the bodies of the French victims were returned home, Mr Charles Pasqua,
interior minister, said Britain, Germany and the US had failed to act when
tipped off about the activities of fundamentalists.
'They have within their borders people who claim to be official
representatives of the FIS (Islamic Salvation Front),' he said. 'We have
already made diplomatic representations to these countries and we will make
more.'
Mr Pasqua said seven Moslem militants in France had been moved to a remote
eastern village. The seven are reported to have been brought together in the
village of Folembray, after having been under house arrest in various parts
of France.
In The Hague, the foreign ministry said the Dutch embassy in Algiers, where
staff had already been reduced to three, would close temporarily because of
fears for their safety.
Belgium strongly advised its nationals to leave the former French territory
and said all travel there should be postponed because of the worsening
security situation.
Violence has grown since the Algerian authorities in January 1992 suspended
elections that the FIS was poised to win. More than 50 foreigners and
thousands of Algerians have been killed since then.
Mr Anwar Haddam, a FIS representative in Washington, yesterday denounced
France's support of Algeria's 'military regime'.
Mr Pasqua said the Algerian government was 'not a model of democracy', but
said that France would help it in its fight against 'terrorism' and that
there was no such thing as 'good and bad terrorists'.
The US State Department said the latest killings 'only reinforce the concern
we have that the (Algerian) government should broaden its political
dialogue' to opposition groups that reject violence.
France, like the US, has been urging Algeria's military-led government into
dialogue with its moderate opponents. But France has found itself sucked
further into the crisis in its former colony than the US and less able to
articulate its policy of reluctant and conditional support for the Algerian
government as a 'lesser evil' than emergence of a fundamentalist Islamic
state.
Le Monde newspaper yesterday suggested that France and the west use economic
aid as a lever to force the Algiers government into political concessions.
But the IMF, which gave Algeria a standby credit in May, and the Paris Club,
which rescheduled its official debt in June, are not readily suited to such
political bargaining.
</TEXT>
