<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Top general angers Kremlin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A senior Russian general who supports military dictatorship and backs a
muscular role for the Russian army in the former Soviet republics is set to
lose his job, military officials said yesterday. The predicted removal of
Gen Alexander Lebed, commander of Russian forces in the break-away
Transdnestr region of Moldova, suggests the Kremlin is seeking to remove
hardliners from the military. However, other Russian military officers
denied Gen Lebed was being forced out. Relations between Gen Lebed, who has
said he will not stay in the military if he is removed from his post, and
the Kremlin reached a nadir last month after the general told Izvestia, the
Russian daily newspaper, that Russia invited attack through its military
weakness and described all Russian politicians, including President Boris
Yeltsin, as 'minuses'.
</TEXT>
