<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / Italian elder statesman dies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Giovanni Spadolini, the Republican politician and intellectual who was a
leading figure in post-war Italy, died in Rome yesterday aged 69. He was a
contemporary historian, newspaper editor and latterly bon vivant elder
statesman. His body was brought to lie in state in the Senate, where he was
a life senator and speaker from 1987 until this year. Mr Spadolini, the
first prime minister from outside the Christian Democrat party under the
post-war republic, was appointed in 1981 to head a five-party coalition when
Italy's political establishment had been shaken by the scandal of the P2
secret masonic lodge, a parallel power structure. His strong personality
held the coalition together for 405 days before being reshuffled. It then
lasted another 82 days. Three times a minister in different governments, he
latterly played an important role as speaker of the Senate, enlivening
debate with his erudition and crusty humour. He challenged the new
Berlusconi government to retain the speaker's post and lost by a single
vote. Mr Spadolini was born in Florence and began his public life teaching
history. He switched to journalism, eventually becoming editor of the
prestigious Corriere della Sera, and entered politics comparatively late, in
1972, on being elected as an independent senator in the Republican lists. He
took on the leadership of the Republican party in 1979 on the death of Mr
Ugo La Malfa and held the post for eight years.
</TEXT>
