<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 94 / DTI clampdown on 'pyramid' schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry is clamping down on 'pyramid' companies
supposedly structured in a way to generate money-for-nothing for their
investors.
In an indication that pyramid schemes are not just a feature of economies
where capitalism is a novelty - such as the collapsed MMM in Russia and
Caritas in Romania - the department said it had wound up four such companies
in the past month.
Pyramid schemes operate by recruiting new subscribers in order to provide
the money required to pay off existing investors. The schemes are ultimately
flawed because they require the generation of an infinite number of new
investors.
A team of department investigators has been scrutinising a number of such
companies recently and is believed to be considering further closures.
After a High Court petition on 'public interest' grounds, the official
receiver was yesterday appointed provisional liquidator to Quillpunch, a
company trading as the Alchemy Foundation.
Quillpunch had been created using assets and subscribers transferred from
Alchemy Marketing and Alchemy (UK), two other companies wound up by the DTI
late last month. They had traded as Alchemy UK. The scheme had approximately
8,000 subscribers.
Last month, the department wound up a similar company called 3T
Publications, which offered a scheme known as FPW or Frequency Programming
World. Customers were asked to send up to Pounds 70 a month to the company,
which said it would redistribute the money between existing subscribers.
A consultative document on reforms to the law dealing with pyramid schemes
is being drawn up by the department. This is likely to be issued by
December.
The department said it was responding to complaints about such
organisations, many of which operate under legal loopholes.
'It's a matter of people's judgment whether to join these schemes,' the
department added. It highlighted a recent ruling from Mr Justice Chadwick
that such schemes 'are bound to fail'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
