<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / S African shop strike settled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A bitter 24-day strike over wages by workers at South Africa's Pick'n Pay
supermarket chain ended yesterday but strikes in other sectors of the
economy continued to hit production, Reuter reports from Johannesburg.
Walkouts in the motor, metal, paper and oil industries and the public sector
hit the country's fragile economy amid government fears that labour unrest
could frighten off investors.
Pick'n Pay, with 350 stores across the country, signed an agreement with the
South African Commercial Catering and Allied Workers' Union giving employees
a 180 rand (Dollars 40) increase and a 1,110 (Dollars 308) minimum wage.
But there was no sign of progress in negotiations over a strike by 25,000
car workers that has brought seven big plants to a halt. 'There was no
substantial progress in our negotiations and therefore we have nothing to
say at this stage,' an official of the National Union of Metalworkers of
South Africa said.
