<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures had a dull but volatile session as the market paused for
breath following Tuesday's strong showing, writes Joel Kibazo.
The first trade in the September contract on the FT-SE 100 was struck at
3,177, some 6 points below its previous close but at a healthy premium to
cash.
Strong profit-taking in the first hour of trading saw the contract retreat
to 3,164, the day's low, for the first of two occasions before bargain
hunting stopped the slide.
The rally that followed took the contract to a peak of 3,184 before another
bout of selling once again sent it to the day's low. The weak opening on
Wall Street only encouraged further selling of September.
It finished at 3,175, down 8 from its previous session but at a 16-point
premium to cash. Volume was very poor at 8,149 lots.
Dealers said the December contract had been trading a point above its fair
value premium of 12 points, an indication of confidence in the contract.
Active dealing in the stock options brought improved turnover in the traded
options sector. Volume at the close was 36,649 contracts, of which 10,584
were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and 2,155 in the Euro FT-SE option. Tesco
was the busiest stock option with 3,370 lots dealt. National power and
Argyll Group were also active.
