<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / UK Company News: H&amp;C 24% higher at midway - Industry growth
driven by housing starts not maintenance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Harrisons &amp; Crosfield, the industrial conglomerate, yesterday voiced concern
over prospects for the housing market as it unveiled a better than expected
24 per cent rise in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 59.9m.
Mr Bill Turcan, chief executive, said industry growth in the first six
months had been driven by new housing starts rather than repairs and
maintenance, where most of H&amp;C's business in the UK arose.
His caution led H&amp;C to hold the interim dividend for the fourth successive
year at 3.6p. Earnings rose 12 per cent to 4.6p.
Mr Turcan was optimistic about the company's prospects for the rest of the
year. Sales in the first half were flat at Pounds 1.1bn, but trading in
H&amp;C's building and timber supplies business remained strong. This division
had returned the fastest growth in the six months with operating profits
ahead by 27 per cent to Pounds 13.5m.
The chemicals business remained competitive, while food and agriculture had
been hit by price pressure. BOCM Pauls, the agriculture and animal feeds
business purchased in 1992, was expected to 'begin to realise its potential
for higher profits', he said.
The group's overall profits included net disposal proceeds of Pounds 6.3m,
but still compared favourably with market expectations of between Pounds 45m
and Pounds 55m.
Mr Turcan said H&amp;C, which has streamlined its diversified portfolio of
businesses, was now ready to strengthen two divisions through acquisition -
timber and building supplies, and the speciality chemicals operation.
H&amp;C last week raised Dollars 273m from the disposal of its Indonesian
plantations, leaving it with debt of Pounds 59m, against Pounds 221m at the
end of the half. The group intends to take advantage of the fragmented UK
building supplies market - where it claims a 5 per cent share - and moves by
global chemicals companies to withdraw from niche markets.
Mr Turcan said H&amp;C was in no rush to spend the money. It would be deposited
to offset tax losses around the world, leaving H&amp;C free to take its time on
acquisitions. He added that H&amp;C had no immediate intention of selling its
remaining plantations in Papua New Guinea. The most likely route was a local
flotation. See Lex
</TEXT>
