FT  04 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Blue Circle sells New World for Pounds 5.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Blue Circle Industries, the UK's largest cement company, has sold its
lossmaking New World Domestic Appliances subsidiary to a management buy-in
team for Pounds 5.5m.
The maker of gas cookers and ovens was part of Birmid Qualcast, which Blue
Circle bought in a hostile Pounds 330m bid in 1988.
The Warrington-based company incurred a Pounds 2.2m operating loss in 1993
on sales of Pounds 39.6m.
Blue Circle will incur a write-off on the value of New World's net assets of
Pounds 8.7m. The total write-off in the accounts to June 1994, after
recognising Pounds 35.1m of goodwill written off against reserves at
acquisition, will therefore be Pounds 43.8m.
Murray Johnstone Private Equity Limited, the venture capital group, funded
the Pounds 5.5m equity portion of the management buy-in and Nat West
Acquisition Finance is providing Pounds 5m of senior debt.
The buy-in is being led by Mr Mike Hassall, and the new company will be
chaired by Mr Jeoff Samson, former chief executive of Yale &amp; Valor and
chairman of Hunterprint, the struggling specialist printer.
Blue Circle said the sale was consistent with its strategy to concentrate on
heavy building materials, heating and bathrooms.
