FT  04 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Restructured Halkin returns to black with
Pounds 1.25m at midway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE GASCOIGNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Halkin Holdings, the accessories and brewing group, announced a profit for
its first six months as a restructured company.
Pre-tax profits at the group, bought by Mr Howard Hodgson, the former
funeral director, in August 1993, were Pounds 1.25m on turnover of Pounds
11.4m for the six months to July 2.
The year-end was changed from March 31 to end-December; for the nine months
to December 31 the group incurred a loss of Pounds 998,000 on turnover of
Pounds 478,000.
The group has ungone a radical restructuring in the past year, acquiring
Ronson, the lighter and aerosol group, for Pounds 10m and LGW, a gift
company now trading as Clifford International, for Pounds 9.5m.
The purchases were funded partly by a Pounds 15m rights issue, and Halkin
said both were performing well.
The company said it was beginning an 'international brand-building
programme' to re-establish the Ronson name. Three new collections of
lighters, pens and watches were being launched.
Clifford International has strengthened its product range, with airline
listings up on the previous year, and the brewery has returned to profits.
Earnings per share were 2.46p, against losses of 17.2p. No interim dividend
is declared, but the board said it intends to recommend a full-year
distribution.
