<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Warburg settles SBC dispute with charity donation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
S. G. Warburg yesterday settled a 'dealing dispute' between itself and Swiss
Bank Corp by agreeing to make a charitable donation on Swiss Bank's behalf.
The London Stock Exchange, which had been asked by SBC to consider whether
Warburg had broken exchange rules, said yesterday it was 'satisfied that no
further action is required'.
The exchange declined to say whether or not its domestic equity rules
committee had decided that Warburg had actually broken the rules, nor did it
state that it was Warburg which had been required to make the charitable
payment.
An earlier sub-committee of that group had determined that Warburg had
violated a rule obliging a marketmaker to fill a 'firm limit order' from a
client when the marketmaker had the opportunity to do so.
Yesterday, Warburg declined to comment on the matter while SBC said it was
happy that the dispute had been settled to the benefit of charity.
The exchange said that the issue which SBC presented 'raised unprecedented
and complex issues in connection with the interpretation of the exchange's
rules'.
In particular, it said there was a need to consult with the Takeover Panel
on rules about firm orders to buy shares during takeover situations.
The dispute stemmed from an unusual offer by Warburg during Enterprise Oil's
contested bid for Lasmo when, days before the offer was to close, it - as
broker to Enterprise - offered a select group of institutional investors in
Lasmo the opportunity to sell their shares at a price well above the market.
SBC is said to have complained that although it had left a firm order to
sell its Lasmo shares, Warburg failed to meet its obligation to do so.
Warburg, in turn, is said to have argued that SBC had left no such order,
and that in any event, marketmakers have an option, but not an obligation,
to fill those orders before offering to buy shares from elsewhere.
It is understood that the exchange's Rules Committee ruled that while the
wording of its rule 4.24(b) is unclear, market convention and practice have
required marketmakers to fill client limit orders such as that placed by
SBC.
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
