<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Rival may join funeral bid battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Great Southern Group, the UK funeral company under siege from Service
Corporation International, of the US, is talking to a potential white knight
 -understood to be one of SCI's US rivals.
Great Southern's share price rose 28p to 708p after it revealed the
discussions. Analysts said a new offer would have to exceed 700p, compared
with SCI's increased bid of 680p.
The potential counter-bidder is one of SCI's two largest competitors in the
US, Vancouver-based Loewen Group and New Orleans-based Stewart Enterprises,
according to sources close to Great Southern. Both are US listed and have
mirrored SCI's acquisitive trail, with Loewen spending Dollars 165m on
purchases last year and Stewart investing close to Dollars 100m.
The latest turn in the battle is a blow to SCI, which yesterday increased
its stake in Great Southern to 30 per cent of the fully diluted share
capital (upon conversion of the preference shares). But SCI is not permitted
to buy at above 680p. In addition, it has been unable to achieve any serious
dialogue with JD Field &amp; Sons, the private company which controls 56 per
cent of Great Southern's ordinary shares.
Mr Bill Heiligbrodt, SCI president, said: 'If there is any real substance
around this statement, then clearly the Field family have decided to sell.
But, as we own 30 per cent of the stock, what sort of credence can be placed
on the offeror.'
Given Great Southern's move to attract a counter bidder, the announcement
appears to herald the end of the Field family's 300-year history of running
an independent funeral group.
SCI has the right to increase its final offer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Great Southern Group.
    Service Corporation International.
    Loewen Group Inc.
    Stewart Enterprises Inc.
</CO>
