<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Ricoh launches court battle against Samsung over patents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two Asian electronics companies are battling over the rights to the
technology behind the facsimile machine record slips which enable users to
keep track of pages sent and the numbers to which faxes are transmitted.
Many users discard the record slips, but the use of the 'administrant data'
technology has prompted Ricoh, the Japanese office equipment maker, to file
a complaint with the US International Trade Commission against Samsung
Electronics, charging the Korean company with patent infringement and
claiming unspecified damages.
Ricoh contends that Samsung has infringed two facsimile patents and has
asked the ITC to prohibit Samsung from importing, marketing, demonstrating,
distributing or selling in the US, fax machines that infringe the patents.
Most fax machine makers pay royalties to use the Ricoh technology under
licence.
Ricoh said it was forced to take action against Samsung after repeated
negotiations over several years had failed to result in a satisfactory
agreement.
The Japanese company has filed a complaint with the ITC and the New Jersey
district court seeking a permanent injunction against Samsung and claiming
damages. The move by Ricoh illustrates the growing friction between Japanese
and Korean companies in international markets, especially in areas where the
Japanese have long been market leaders.
The two countries agreed last December to resume co-operation on patent
processing issues, after a gap of seven years following Japanese complaints
that Korean companies were infringing on patents.
Japanese electronics makers have dominated the facsimile market, which last
year was worth Y355bn (Pounds 2.3bn) in Japan alone, according to the
Electronic Industries Association of Japan. The biggest seller, Ricoh, also
sold 2.3m fax machines in the US last year, according to BIS Strategic
Decisions, a high technology consultancy, which forecast a rise to 3.9m in
1998.
However, Korean and Taiwanese manufacturers have increasingly eaten into the
Japanese share, particularly at the lower end of the market for thermal
paper faxes. Exports of fax machines from Japan fell 13 per cent to Y227bn
in 1993 from the previous year, according to the EIAJ.
The Japanese dominance is also being threatened by the impact of a high yen
which has eroded the price competitiveness of fax machines made in Japan.
Ms Debra Waggoner, of the American Electronics Association, said yesterday:
'For the electronics industry, protection of intellectual property rights is
crucial.'
Noting that Ricoh has chosen to fight the battle in US courts, she said that
the US had been getting 'signals' from Japanese companies 'that they are
going to be more pro-active in protecting their rights'.
Sanctions fears rebound, Page 4
</TEXT>
