<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Observer: Bluff Bob Horton
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack chairman Bob Horton really must be sensitive about the size of his
Pounds 120,000 a year salary. How else do you explain his odd bet with
signal workers' boss Jimmy Knapp on BBC radio's Today programme yesterday
morning?
Horton promised to give to charity the net difference between his salary and
Knapp's, if it would help break the strike deadlock. Knapp earns Pounds
46,000, so this would mean that Horton would have to hand over Pounds
44,400.
A friendly accountant at Touche Ross calculates that if Horton paid the
Pounds 44,400 over as a net Gift Aid payment, the charity could reclaim tax
of Pounds 14,800 leaving it with a total of Pounds 59,200. Horton would then
receive tax relief at 15 per cent on Pounds 8,800 so the net cost to him
would be Pounds 35,520. Sadly, Knapp declined to call Horton's bluff.
</TEXT>
