<TEXT>
Sir, Democrat Jim Hightower, who described President Clinton as
'thixotropic' (Observer: 'Quality test', August 3), may know his politics
but he doesn't know his chemistry. A thixotropic substance is fluid when it
is stirred and solid when left to stand (not, as he apparently said, solid
until heat is applied).
But his analogy works. The message is: if you want a solid president, stop
stirring.
