<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is to be the year of the Lucan. Twenty years ago come November Lord
Lucan tried to kill his wife and killed his children's nanny instead. He
then disappeared. He is almost certainly dead but the absence of a body, and
the fact that Lucan had rich and influential friends, has given
gossipmongers a field day. True Stories; Dead Lucky (Channel 4 at 9.30) is
the first of an avalanche of speculative programmes.
This is a tabloid kind of evening, with another subject more usually found
in the popular press. In the late 1970s burly George Roberts became Julia
Grant. His sex change operation, and adjustment to his new life, was filmed
by a television crew. Now the cameras return to discover how Julia has fared
during her time as a woman. A Change of Sex (BBC 2 at 9.30) starts
with a repeat of the 1979 programmes.
In its early years there was always one night at the Proms devoted to
Wagner. To celebrate the 100th year this tradition is revived as the BBC
National Orchestra of Wales kicks off with the most performed piece at the
Proms, the overture to Tannhauser (BBC 1 at 10.35).
</TEXT>
