<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Approval gained for tunnel trippers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Anglo-French inter-governmental commission has approved limited
passenger services through the Channel tunnel.
The commission has given permission for invitation-only passenger rail
operations, the final stage of preparation for running regular public
services.
Trains will be run at less than full load with increasing frequency, under
the supervision of the commission, which must satisfy itself on safety.
Trains will carry invited passengers and their cars between the Cheriton
terminal at Folkestone and the Sangatte terminal near Calais.
Eurotunnel shareholders, travel agents, journalists and politicians will be
among the first groups invited. The company hopes to launch a regular
service in October.
The commission's decision also covers high-speed Eurostar passenger trains
between London, Paris and Brussels.
</TEXT>
