<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Concern on fall in grants to housing associations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government grants to housing associations to fund the cost of low-cost homes
for rent or sale will fall next year, in spite of warnings that this will
make it harder for them to raise capital.
Mr David Curry, housing minister, yesterday announced the ceiling for
housing association grants would fall from 62 per cent of the cost of a new
home to 58 per cent in 1995-96. This is higher than the target of 55 per
cent set two years ago for 1995-96.
Lenders have warned that a fall in rates below the present level would make
it much harder for associations to raise the balance of the cost on the
capital markets.
Nationwide building society, one of the largest lenders to the sector, said
last night that it would have to look much more closely at the viability of
lending to associations. It said: 'Whilst we are pleased that the government
hasn't reduced the grant rate to 55 per cent we feel that at an average rate
of 58 per cent many housing associations may find it difficult to secure
their private-finance requirements.'
Associations raise about Pounds 1bn a year to top up government grants to
build subsidised homes.
The lower grant rate could make many lenders reluctant to lend the 42 per
cent needed to top up the grant. Tenanted homes are commonly valued at 50
per cent of their vacant value, with lenders wanting cover of 150 per cent
of the loan. Associations are now having to pledge older properties as
security for new loans, which in effect cuts many newer and specialist
associations out of development.
The National Federation of Housing Associations has warned that the cuts in
the grant rate will reduce the number of associations that are able to
borrow and build homes.
Mr Jim Coulter, federation director, warned last night that the need to
borrow a higher proportion of the cost would put up rents. 'On average rents
for new homes at this grant level are likely to be 30 per cent higher in
1996 than 1993 rents,' he said.
Mr Curry said that he was confident that associations would be able to
maintain their building programmes at the new rate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
