<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Meter problems confuse electricity users
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thousands of industrial and commercial consumers of electricity are facing
confusion over their bills as a result of severe metering problems in the
section of the supply market recently opened to competition.
Four months ago medium to large users were given a choice on who should be
their supplier and about 12,000 took advantage of this. However many have no
firm idea how much their electricity is costing and are working from
estimates.
According to the Major Energy Users' Council some consumers fear they will
never be given accurate bills covering the last four months. Mr Richard
Wills, the council's technical director, said: 'The degree of incompetence
on the part of the electricity industry is breathtaking. Our members are
having to divert a horrendous amount of management time to sorting out the
mess.'
Among the causes of the problem is that about 5,000 consumers are still
awaiting installation of special meters or have had meters installed which
are not working properly. This is partly due to meter shortages in some
areas, although some companies share the blame for slowness in appointing
meter operators.
Reasons for meters not working properly include incorrect installation - in
some cases because of poor training - and a failure to ensure that the meter
is connected to telecommunication lines.
Relatively sophisticated 'code 5' meters are needed because they can gauge
how much power is used every half hour and can be read remotely by the
electricity bill settlement authorities.
Power prices are determined by the pool for every half hour, and vary
according to demand.
The thousands of customers without 'code 5' meters are facing weekly visits
from the local electricity companies' readers to enable the bill settlements
department at the pool to make estimates.
Monthly meter readings were the norm before April 1.
The inconvenience caused by the more frequent meter readings is
counterbalanced to some extent by electricity suppliers sending bills which
in general underestimate what will eventually have to be paid, thus helping
customers' cashflow.
The suppliers say part of the confusion has been caused by late decisions by
Offer, the industry regulator, on several issues affecting the market. One
decision was to introduce competition in meter reading. Previously it was
the preserve of regional electricity companies.
A regional company executive said: 'Introducing competition in both meter
reading and electricity supply at the same time has proved too much.'
Ms Margaret McKinlay, pool chief executive, said that deciding who should
install the meter and associated technology had proved a bureaucratic
nightmare. The system which was introduced involved too many people and
organisations.
The pool has set up a task force of eight people to sort out the settlements
problem.
In spite of the problems many companies will benefit financially from the
introduction of competition because of the fall in prices that has resulted.
Estimates of annual bill reductions of at least 4 per cent are common.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
