<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Imro to weigh use of derivatives and emerging markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Imro, the self-regulatory body for the fund-management industry, is to look
at fund managers which invest in emerging markets and those which use
derivatives. The watchdog's aim is to ensure that investors are not being
put at risk.
Mr Philip Thorpe, Imro chief executive, said that while there was no
evidence that investor protection was being compromised, 'we are always
concerned where there is a bandwagon effect'. The performance of emerging
markets relative to domestic or developed stock markets had led to keen
investor interest in this sector, he said.
He added: 'We are just taking a look and seeing if there is cause for
concern.' He was particularly concerned to see that investors understood the
risks both of emerging markets and of derivatives.
Mr Thorpe's remarks came as Imro unveiled its first quarterly 'performance
indicators' report, detailing the extent to which the watchdog is meeting
its performance objectives.
The report showed that 152 separate complaints had been received, of which
71 related to 'unsuitable' advice given to clients. Of these, about
one-third relate to individuals who had been encouraged to transfer out of
their occupational pension scheme and into a personal pension.
Most of these complaints are against Imro member companies which are large
chains of independent financial advisers who will soon join the Personal
Investment Authority.
Separately, Mr Thorpe said that regulators might eventually review their
rules relating to 'soft commissions' - the procedure by which fund managers
accept services from brokers in exchange for agreeing to transact minimum
amounts of trades through them. One Imro member, Abbey Unit Trust Managers,
recently became the first group to be disciplined for abuse of the rules by
accepting free foreign travel for its fund managers.
</TEXT>
