<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Railtrack plans for the unthinkable: What the result of the
supervisors' ballot could mean for the signalling dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The outcome of the railway supervisors' ballot due to be announced this
afternoon could have a crucial impact on the signalling dispute.
Officials of the RMT transport union are publicly confident that supervisors
will support action so that they can join strikes on Friday August 12 and on
the following Monday and Tuesday. This would follow the seven days' notice
of strike action required by law.
But in private officials seem less sure of the ballot result and are playing
down its significance.
The 1,200 supervisors oversee the work of the 4,600 signalling workers, as
well as instructing them and testing their work.
The work of the supervisors, who earn an average of about Pounds 20,000, is
critical in ensuring safety.
Railtrack estimates that just 385 of the supervisors belong to the RMT and
have been ballotted - about a third of the total number. If they reject the
strike call the pressure on the union to make a swift settlement will be
substantial. Such a vote would undermine the solidarity of the signalling
workers and make it easier for Railtrack to persuade an increasing number to
ignore strike calls.
But both sides are planning contingencies in the expectation of a Yes vote
from the supervisors.
A fortnight ago Railtrack officials seemed unprepared to contemplate such an
outcome. They still hoped that a settlement could be reached before there
was any question of supervisors joining the strike action.
Since then management has had to start preparing for the unthinkable. It is
clear that Railtrack and British Rail would not be able to run as many
trains as they have been in the past few weeks if the supervisors joined the
strikes.
But Railtrack said that it was impossible to estimate how serious an impact
that would have on services. Observers believe that some supervisors will
not heed a strike call, partly for fear of managerial reprisals.
Whatever sympathy supervisors may have for signalling workers it is by no
means certain it will translate into joining a dispute that is only
indirectly relevant to them.
</TEXT>
