FT  04 AUG 94 / Gibraltar's top lawyer quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The attorney general of Gibraltar, Mr John Blackburn Gittings, has resigned
11 months before completion of his three-year term in office. The governor
of Gibraltar, Field Marshal Sir John Chapple, last night announced that Mr
Gittings had resigned early because of 'difference of views' between the two
men. The governor said that the attorney general's decision to resign was
'unconnected with questions of legal advice or current public issues'. The
resignation is likely to refuel the controversy surrounding the handling of
a British and Danish police investigation into allegations of fraud linked
to a major property development in Gibraltar. Four Danes are currently
standing trial in Denmark after being charged with defrauding a local
construction company JPC which was involved in the Gibraltar property
development. The charges relate to payments totalling Pounds 5.4m. Mr
Gittings has been present at police interviews with local officials in
Gibraltar in connection with the alleged fraud. In recent weeks he has also
requested the Swiss authorities to provide information of bank accounts
related to the police investigation.
