<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 94 / Beef export inquiry puts pressure on Dublin coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MCMANUS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ireland's coalition government came under pressure yesterday following
criticism of Mr Albert Reynolds, the prime minister and former industry and
commerce minister, for his decision to grant more than IPounds 100m (Pounds
99m) in credit insurance for beef exports to Iraq six years ago.
Following publication of a long-awaited official report into the affair
earlier this week, Mr Dick Spring, the deputy prime minister and Labour
party leader, described Mr Reynolds' actions as a 'major failure of public
policy'.
The report has further strained relations between Mr Reynolds' Fianna Fail
and Labour, the junior government partner, already at odds over Northern
Ireland and a labour dispute at Team Aer Lingus, the maintenance arm of the
Irish airline.
As industry and commerce minister, Mr Reynolds approved export credit
guarantees to the Goodman Group, Ireland's biggest beef processor and
exporter, for meat exports to Iraq. The credits were granted between 1987
and 1988.
A tribunal was set up to investigate allegations against Goodman Group in
May 1991, before the Labour-Fianna Fail coalition government was formed in
1992.
Its report concluded that Irish taxpayers were exposed to a potential
liability of more than IPounds 100m as a result of the insurance cover
extended by Mr Reynolds. It also said the decision on credit insurance was
taken by Mr Reynolds 'against the professional advice available to him'.
'The benefit accruing or likely to accrue to the Irish economy from this
situation would be minimal . . . and would not justify the risk involved in
granting export insurance in the amounts granted,' it said.
The report has undermined Mr Reynolds' assertions at the weekend that he had
been 'totally vindicated' by it.
The chairman of the inquiry accepted that Mr Reynolds had the right to
extend the export credits, but said a more detailed investigation should
have been carried out.
Goodman Group had intended to export a large proportion of the beef to Iraq
from European Union intervention stocks but not from sources within the
Irish republic. The benefits to the Irish economy of this were 'illusory
rather than real', the report said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
