<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Dollar issues surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO, SAQIB QURESHI and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in the dollar saw internationally traded stocks stand out
strongly. ICI, still benefiting from recent strong figures, gained 23 at
860p, while Reuters added 21 at 489p, Glaxo 21 at 594p and Unilever 23 at
1046p.
Unilever is due to report second-quarter results on Friday, and Strauss
Turnbull reiterated its positive stance. The house forecasts a slight
decline in profits to Pounds 588m but expects a second half boost from a
recovery in European demand and the benefits of recent corporate
restructuring.
Cable and Wireless, another dollar beneficiary, received additional support
from a Hoare Govett note which argues that the company's non- Hong Kong
operations are valued at 'close to a five-year low' and a share price of
580p would reflect the true valuation more closely. The shares strengthened
15 to 451p.
Household goods group Reckitt &amp; Colman, usually a niggardly market
performer, jumped 25 to 613p as a reshuffle at SG Warburg prompted the house
to boost its recommendation to buy from hold.
The house acknowledges that earnings growth is not one of the company's big
strengths but adds that the stock is on a 10-year p/e relative low and yield
relative high and sees a short term 10 per cent upside in the share price.
Insurer Commercial Union fell 9 to 539p on nervousness ahead of the expected
rights issue needed to fund the acquisition of Groupe Victoire, of France.
Among food retailers, bid target William Low slipped 4 to 336p as hopes for
a counter-bid from Tesco receded slightly. J. Sainsbury, which last week bid
Pounds 210m for the Scottish supermarket group, gained 7 at 419p. Tesco,
whose Pounds 155m agreed offer for Low two weeks ago was trumped by
Sainsbury, put on 6 1/2 at 243p.
Tate &amp; Lyle advanced 7 to 442p, with Credit Lyonnais Laing said to be
recommending the stock.
A mixed trading statement from Burton was taken positively by the market and
the shares ended the session 3 ahead at 59 1/2 p. Disappointing sales during
the 22 weeks to the end of July were offset by better than expected gross
margins. The company also said it was closing its 'IS' discount chain.
Forecasts were edged upwards, with Hoare Govett now looking for Pounds 42m
this year and Pounds 63m in 1995. The broker also upgraded the stock.
Brewers and spirits groups responded to reports of increased sales during
the recent spell of hot weather in the UK and the government's Green Paper
on extending licencing hours. Bass advanced 13 to 568p, Grand Metropolitan 9
to 424p and JD Wetherspoon 19 to 395p.
Agency broker James Capel placed the rump of the recent rights issue from
Greycoat, 21.75m shares being sold to a range of institutions at 14 1/2 p.
Greycoat firmed a penny to 15 1/2 p. Elsewhere, MEPC continued to benefit
from reports of its finance-raising exercise in Australia, gaining 12 at
470p.
Meanwhile, Capel, a re-knowned bull of the property sector, reported
unexpectedly strong rental growth, particularly in London's West End and
City office markets. The broker recommended Land Securities, up 16 at 673p,
and British Land, ahead 9 at 432p, as being well placed to benefit from the
renewed optimism.
British Aerospace improved 10 to 511p after a positive note from Hoare
Govett, the group's broker, landed on clients' desks yesterday. The focus of
the circular is BAe's long term potential but the broker also increased its
current year profits forecast by Pounds 10m to Pounds 170m.
Margins worries at vehicle distributor Cowie Group sent the shares tumbling
12 to 256p, after the group reported a robust set of interim figures with
profits up 32 per cent to Pounds 20.5m. Lex Service, which recently came
under similar pressure following its results, relinquished 7 1/2 to 422p.
Engineering company TI closed 15 up at 402p ahead of interim figures due
tomorrow.
Lucas Industries put on 8 at 203p, with a big buyer of the shares said to
have been waiting in the wings.
Resignation due to ill health of the deputy chairman at Hall Engineering
left the shares trailing 13 at 180p.
British Airways was restrained to a rise of only 3 at 421p in trade of 3.8m.
Dealers reported some nervousness ahead of today's publication of July
traffic figures.
Yorkshire Chemicals, the colours and dye based group, jumped 29 to 421p
after announcing first-half profits of Pounds 7.2m, at the top end of City
expectations. Holliday Chemicals moved up 13 to 235p ahead of next week's
interim results.
Construction group Havelock Europa moved ahead 8 to 177p after it was chosen
by Camelot, operator of the national lottery, to fulfil a substantial
proportion of its requirements. Elsewhere in the sector, Smith New Court
recommended housebuilder firms Bryant Group at 154p and Beazer Homes at
157p.
