<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Latest data fail to provide
fresh impetus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks paused after a two-day rally yesterday in spite of more economic
data which may help to delay the Federal Reserve's next move to tighten
monetary policy, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished down 1.95 at 3,796.22, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 0.45 at 460.56. Volume on
the Big Board amounted to 295.6m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite edged up 0.12 to close
at 439.74, while the Nasdaq composite eased 0.05 to 724.80.
When the session commenced, stocks appeared to be heading for their third
big gain in a row. The Dow industrials opened 12 points higher, building on
a powerful 67-point advance which began late last week.
Yesterday's economic news provided additional support to a scenario which
had triggered the rally on Friday. The Commerce Department announced that
sales of new single-family homes had dropped by 14.1 per cent in June to an
annualised rate of 591,000. Analysts, who had expected a much more modest
decline, said the downturn was evidence of the effect of more restrictive
credit conditions. The data supported the view, advanced by last week's GDP
report, that the Fed would hold off its next move to put up interest rates.
In spite of the favourable news, stocks ran out of steam. Most equity
investors were content to sit tight, delaying their next big moves until
after Friday's crucial employment data. The keenly watched report may
provide the Fed with the last piece of evidence it needs to make a decision
on when to lift rates again.
However, investors were showing no inclination to cut and run. Stocks across
the board hovered within a tight range of their opening values, mirroring
activity in the bond market.
In pharmaceuticals, investors shrugged off an early report that SmithKline
Beecham was negotiating an asset swap with American Cyanamid. But minutes
from the close, news broke that another company, American Home Products, was
offering to acquire shares in Cyanamid for 95 cents each.
Trading in both issues was halted on the annoucement, with AHP at Dollars 56
3/4 , down Dollars  3/4 on the day, and Cyanamid at Dollars 63 3/4, up
Dollars 3/4. SmithKline added Dollars 1/2 to finish at Dollars 32 1/8.
The takeover bid gave a late boost to the entire sector, with Warner Lambert
jumping Dollars 4 to Dollars 68 1/2, Schering Plough up Dollars 3 1/2 to
Dollars 66 1/4 and and Pfiser ahead Dollars 2 to Dollars 63 1/2.
Among the Dow industrials, a few cyclical issues showed improvement.
International Paper was Dollars 1 3/8 stronger at Dollars 75 1/4 amid a
general upturn among paper and pulp stocks. Elsewhere, Georgia Pacific
gained Dollars 3 1/4 at Dollars 69 1/8 and Scott Paper added Dollars 1 1/2
at Dollars 60.
United Technologies climbed as high as Dollars 64 1/4 during the morning but
dropped back to close at Dollars 63, a net gain of Dollars 1/4. Over the
last few sessions the stock has retraced some of the losses it had suffered
on the release of its second-quarter results.
Bethlehem Steel, up Dollars 3/8 at Dollars 23 5/8, appreciated amid reports
of higher prices being paid by Chrysler for raw materials. National Steel
moved Dollars 1 higher to Dollars 22 5/8 .
</TEXT>
