<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Markets Report: Dollar rises above Y100
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conciliatory statements from Japanese officials yesterday helped the market
overcome fears about a trade war between the US and Japan, driving the
dollar above Y100, writes Philip Gawith.
The markets took a benign view of the breakdown in talks, buoyed by comments
from a Japanese Foreign Ministry official that talks might resume in early
September.
The dollar finished in London more than 1 1/2 yen firmer at Y100.415 from
Y98.85. It was also higher against the D-Mark, ending at DM1.5814 from
DM1.5743. The US currency showed little further change at the New York close
at Y100.34 and DM1.5824.
In the UK, interest rate sentiment was improved by the Bank of England's
latest inflation report and a further calming of worries about an imminent
interest rate rise.
Three-month sterling LIBOR traded at 5 9/16 per cent, down from 5 3/4 per
cent on Monday. Short sterling futures also recovered, with the September
contract closing four basis points up at 94.21. Prices firmed further to
94.28 after the release of the inflation report.
The trade weighted sterling index finished firmer at 79.3 from 79, but the
pound weakened after the release of the Bank of England's monetary report,
which was more bullish than expected on inflation. The UK currency closed in
London at DM2.4346 from DM2.4221. It was little changed against the dollar
at Dollars 1.5396.
Trade in Europe was thin as holiday spirit took hold. The Italian lira
remained weak, finishing unchanged at L1,003 against the D-Mark.
Analysts were split as to whether the dollar's breach of Y100 marked a
change in sentiment, or simply a temporary recovery before the downward
trend was resumed.
Two factors seemed to underpin the dollar's firmness: the belief in some
quarters that the Clinton administration is pursuing a strong dollar, rather
than a benign, neglect policy; and the view that the trade row will be
resolved.
The market is clearly of the view that both parties want a deal badly, and
hence will achieve one before the end-September deadline.
Mr Steve Hannah, head of research at Industrial Bank of Japan in London,
cited a further factor: a change in US - Japan capital flows. 'We have noted
some quite important switching out of yen assets into US assets by
international investors. There may be a tide turning here on the yen. People
are showing much more of a preparedness to risk a few per cent loss on the
currency. Increasingly, people are getting attracted to the higher yields in
the US.'
Mr Hannah added that the dollar had the potential to rise to Y102-3 before
the September deadline.
In contrast, Mr Nick Stamenkovic, economist at DKB International in London,
said that although the market was taking the view that a compromise trade
deal would be reached, he would not rule out a further bout of yen strength.
The Bank of England, in its daily monetary operations, underlined the
message that interest rates remained unchanged. After forecasting a shortage
of Pounds 1.1bn, it offered early assistance to the market of Pounds 850m.
The Bank later provided a further Pounds 475m after revising the shortage to
Pounds 1.3bn. Overnight money traded between 2 and 5 per cent.
The Bank's accommodating stance helped douse fears of a rise in interest
rates, reflected in the better performance of short sterling and cash rates
in the money market.
The fall in the level of three-month money should assist the Bank in
handling this Friday's Treasury bill tender.
Markets continued to be much occupied with last week's treasury bill auction
which fuelled speculation of higher interest rates. Following earlier near
blanket condemnation of the Bank, some revisionist voices have started to
appear.
One money market source was scathing about the reaction of the City and much
press comment, saying it had been at best mischievous, at worst
manipulative. 'I think it was downright irresponsible,' he said.
Noting that the Bank's inflation bulletin suggested that they did not
believe there were large inflation pressures in the economy, he continued:
'You get the impression that the market is much more concerned about
inflation than the Bank is.'
Mr Hannah of IBJ said Friday's events were just an 'unsubtle' way of
preparing the market for higher rates. 'The Bank is experienced enough to
know exactly how the market would react.'
He said they were part of a pattern of events, including Mr Eddie George's
Mansion House speech, where he said rate rises were inevitable, and his
comments in the most recent monetary minutes, that there was an advantage in
raising rates before inflation rose.
Mr Hannah said the Bank's activities had had the desired impact of putting
the market on interest rate alert. This meant the UK would probably avoid
the ructions that followed the first policy tight-ening in the US earlier
this year. 'It has to be regarded as successful monetary management,' he
added.
</TEXT>
