   By VINCENT BOLAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Czechoslovak Airlines (CSA), which is seeking a strategic partner to replace
Air France, posted losses of Kcs273.2m (Dollars 9.75m) in the first six
months of this year, writes Vincent Boland in Prague.
This is less than half the deficit in the same period last year, when CSA
lost Kcs629m. The airline said improved revenues from domestic and
international ticket sales and tightly controlled costs, held to 1993
levels, contributed to the better performance.
Passenger numbers in-creased and seating capacity rose to 59.2 per cent from
53.6 per cent, with routes to western Europe showing a 10 per cent increase
in capacity.
CSA is in talks with several international airlines on strategic
co-operation.
