<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / International Company News: Earnings warning hits Newbridge
Networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Newbridge Networks, until recently one of North America's best-performing
technology companies, saw its share value drop almost a third yesterday
after the company warned that first-quarter earnings would not match
analysts' expectations.
Ottawa-based Newbridge has emerged as a leader in the development of
asynchronous mode transmission (ATM) switches and frame relay equipment.
These products are a crucial link in the rapidly growing transfer of
interactive information across telephone lines and computer networks.
Newbridge claims to have captured about half the North American market for
ATM wide-area network switches. Its customers include phone companies,
government agencies and universities.
Newbridge shares tumbled CDollars 17.87 to close at CDollars 40.38 on the
Toronto Stock Exchange. They reached a peak of CDollars 97.50 a year ago,
but have gradually lost ground in line with investors' general disillusion
with the high-technology sector, and concerns that Newbridge's share price
exaggerated its earnings potential. At its peak, the share price was equal
to more than 60 times earnings.
The share-price shake-out follows Newbridge's announcement that earnings for
the three months ended July would fall short of the 41 US cents a share
posted in the preceding three months. However, the company said that
earnings for the quarter - to be published on August 23 - would be higher
than last year's first-quarter of 30 cents a share.
Revenues, orders and an end of quarter backlog have broken records but have
been offset by higher expenses. The jump in expenses was ascribed to
expanded research and development staffing and a 'very busy' trade show and
advertising programme.
Mr Terry Matthews, chief executive and Newbridge's largest single
shareholder, is no stranger to the vicissitudes of North American
high-technology companies. He was a co-founder in the 1970s of Mitel
Corporation, the Canadian telephone equipment maker, which enjoyed a period
of rapid growth but suffered severe financial problems in the late 1980s.
Mr Matthews left Mitel in 1986, shortly after British Telecommunications
bought a controlling stake. He joined Newbridge shortly afterwards. BT sold
its Mitel shares at a heavy loss in mid-1992.
Newbridge's sales have more than quadrupled in the past four years. Wood
Gundy, the Canadian investment house, recently estimated fiscal 1994 sales
at USDollars 547m. Although the growth rate is expected to slow, Wood Gundy
said annual demand for its advanced network systems would grow by at least
40 per cent over the next two years.
</TEXT>
