<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Lionheart warns on profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM DELLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares of Lionheart fell 1 3/4 p to 7p yesterday after the Cheshire-based
manufacturer of paintbrushes and bathroom fittings, announced a boardroom
reshuffle and issued a profits warning.
The company said that its results for the first half of the current year
would be 'materially lower than anticipated' reflecting 'cautious and
erratic consumer demand'.
A recent review of operating expenses led to annualised savings of some
Pounds 2m, the company said, and a reduction of more than Pounds 400,000 in
annualised head office costs via a restructured board.
Mr David Railton, operations director, Mr David Kay, finance director and Mr
Michael Tuttle, a non-executive director, have all left the company; Mr Mark
Walker, previously financial controller, has been appointed group finance
director.
The consequent redundancy and restructuring costs will be charged to the
first half results. Albert E Sharp, the company's broker, revised its
interim profits estimate down from Pounds 2.2m to Pounds 500,000 pre-tax and
anticipates a provision of about Pounds 700,000 to cover the costs.
In March, Lionheart announced a return to the black with pre-tax profits of
Pounds 1.77m for the 1993 year. Mr Paul Lever, chairman, said at that time
that an acquisition was likely 'within months'.
